08794nam a22010335i 9780812297171DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122971717 a10.9783/97808122971712doi  a(DE-B1597)563183  a(OCoLC)1156136201  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHT361b.H76 2020 7aSOC0260302bisacsh00aHow Ideas Shape Urban Political Development /ced. by Timothy P. R. Weaver, Richardson Dilworth. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe City in the Twenty-First Century00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: Urban Political Development and the Politics of Ideas -- t1. Ideas, Interests, Institutions, and Urban Political Development -- tPART I. Ideas in American City Political Development -- t2. How Policy Paradigms Change: Lessons from Chicago’s Urban Renewal Program -- t3. The Idea of Blight in Baltimore -- t4. How Ideas Stopped an Expressway in Philadelphia -- t5. manufacturing Decline: The Conservative Construction of Urban Crisis in Detroit -- tPART II. Ideas in national Urban Policy -- t6. The Neoliberal City and the Racial Idea -- t7. Contested Conceptions of Pluralism Between Cities and Congress over National Civil Rights Legislation -- t8. Ideas in US Education Policy: Reform, Localism, and Immigrant youths -- t9. Ideas, Institutions, Intercurrence, and the Community Reinvestment Act -- tPART III. Ideas and Urban Political Development in Comparative Context -- t10. Immigrant Identities and Integration in the United States and Canada -- t11. “Trying out our Ideas”: Enterprise Zones in the United States and the United Kingdom -- tPART IV. Ideas in Urban Political Development in the Global South -- t12. Ideas, Framing, and Interests in Urban Contention: The Case of Santiago, Chile -- t13. Ideas, Politics, and Urban Development in China -- t14. Politics of Dwelling: Divergent Ideas of Home in Kolkata -- t15. Policy mobility and Urban Fantasies: The Case of African Cities -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA collection of international case studies that demonstrate the importance of ideas to urban political developmentIdeas, interests, and institutions are the "holy trinity" of the study of politics. Of the three, ideas are arguably the hardest with which to grapple and, despite a generally broad agreement concerning their fundamental importance, the most often neglected. Nowhere is this more evident than in the study of urban politics and urban political development.The essays in How Ideas Shape Urban Political Development argue that ideas have been the real drivers behind urban political development and offer as evidence national and international examples—some unique to specific cities, regions, and countries, and some of global impact. Within the United States, contributors examine the idea of "blight" and how it became a powerful metaphor in city planning; the identification of racially-defined spaces, especially black cities and city neighborhoods, as specific targets of neoliberal disciplinary practices; the paradox of members of Congress who were active supporters of civil rights legislation in the 1950s and 1960s but enjoyed the support of big-city political machines that were hardly liberal when it came to questions of race in their home districts; and the intersection of national education policy, local school politics, and the politics of immigration. Essays compare the ways in which national urban policies have taken different shapes in countries similar to the United States, namely, Canada and the United Kingdom. The volume also presents case studies of city-based political development in Chile, China, India, and Africa—areas of the world that have experienced a more recent form of urbanization that feature deep and intimate ties and similarities to urban political development in the Global North, but which have occurred on a broader scale.Contributors: Daniel Béland, Debjani Bhattacharyya, Robert Henry Cox, Richardson Dilworth, Jason Hackworth, Marcus Anthony Hunter, William Hurst, Sally Ford Lawton, Thomas Ogorzalek, Eleonora Pasotti, Joel Rast, Douglas S. Reed, Mara Sidney, Lester K. Spence, Vanessa Watson, Timothy P. R. Weaver, Amy Widestrom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aCities and townsxPolitical aspects. 0aPolitical development. 0aUrban policy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aGeneral.  aSocial Science.  aUrban Studies.1 aBhattacharyya, Debjani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBéland, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCox, robert Henry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDilworth, Richardson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDilworth, Richardson, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHackworth, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunter, Marcus Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHurst, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawton, Sally Ford, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOgorzalek, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPasotti, Eleonora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRast, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReed, Douglas S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat